EGHHS Families ‚Äì
Students will be able to pick up their Chromebooks with other supplies through a scheduled appointment on 9/3 and 9/4. Please contact Lovena Clark at lclark@eagles.edu to make arrangements.

Eagle Sky Academy Families ‚Äì
EES ESA students will be able to pick up Chromebooks and other items on Friday, September 4th. The delivery will work similarly as it was in the spring with the pickup happening in the bus lane.

We will begin at 9 am using the following schedule:
9:00 Kindergarten. 9:15 1st grade
9:30 2nd grade 9:45 3rd grade
10:00 4th grade 10:15 5th grade

If you are unable to make the connection at this time please contact Ms. Stidham or Mr. Scroggins to make alternative arrangements.

For EMS and EHS ESA students be sure to pick up your Chromebooks and get photos taken on Thursday 9/3‚Äîplease follow the directions sent out by the schools.

We have had several concerns regarding the audio of our Superintendent Informational Broadcast. We have investigated and tried to fix it.

We have also had several people that have been able to access the audio and video totally fine. If you are struggling, please check your speed settings on YouTube as well as your volume when opening the video. If this is not working, please try another device.

Another helpful tip: Try searching ‚ÄúElma School District‚Äù and pulling up the video directly from YouTube!

We are very sorry for the inconvenience! We are working hard to provide the best that we can. We will continue to improve in the future.

post_text:
We would like to take the time to recognize and honor our staff members that will be retiring after the 2019-20 school year. Today, we will be recognizing Ms. Wade! Here are some questions she answered for us:

What is your job for the Elma School District? Kindergarten Teacher

How long have you been in this position? 16 years

What do you love most about your job? The kids and my team.

What are your plans after retirement? Watching my one granddaughter, subbing some, and traveling.

What is your best memory from teaching? / What will you miss the most? Having my former students stop by in the mornings or after school. I will miss my team and the planning that takes place to teach and inspire our Kindergarten kids.

post_text:
We would like to take the time to recognize and honor our staff members that will be retiring after the 2019-20 school year. Our first is Ms. Whipple! Here are some questions she answered for us:

1. What is your job for the Elma School District? Kindergarten Teacher

2. How long have you been in this position? 28 years

3. What do you love most about your job? The KIDS!! The smiles, the hugs, the questions, the eagerness, the pride they take in their work, their love for learning and feeling the sense of accomplishment along with them.

4. What are your plans after retirement? Traveling in our fifth wheel, volunteering in the community, and relaxing at home.

5. What is your best memory from teaching? / What will you miss the most? My best memory is working with an awesome kindergarten team. Even though it has changed over the years, the knowledge they all shared with me has been a mainstay throughout my teaching career. I will miss all the people I have worked with over the years but what I will miss most is the KIDS!

Our third, fourth, and fifth grade staff is offering a one-time curbside pickup for learning materials including each students personal school supplies and Ready Math workbook. This one-time curbside pickup will be Thursday, April 23rd. The fifth grade pickup will be in the Elementary School bus lane from 11:00 am to 12:00 noon. The third grade pickup will be in front of the Elma Elementary main office in the fire lane from 9:00 am to 10:00 am. The fourth grade pickup will be in front of the Elma Elementary main office in the fire lane from 10:00 am to 11:00 am. If you are not available during this time, all three grades will have an evening pick up at the same locations from 6:00 pm to 7:00 pm. We are asking that during these pickups all parents and students stay in their vehicles and follow social distancing practices. Have a great evening!

Greg Scroggins
Elma Elementary Asst Principal

We are taking time to spotlight district staff members, and our first is Mr. Arnold! He are some questions he answered for us:

1. What do you teach? Math
2. What grade level do you teach? 7th
3. How long have you taught? This is my 41st year
4. What do you love most about teaching? The opportunity to work with great students and staff who make me laugh every day.
5. What are your hobbies? Woodworking and gardening
6. What is one fun fact about yourself? Next year, I will have taught a grandmother, her daughter, and her granddaughter.

post_text: On Wednesday night, the 8th grade girls varsity basketball team ended their season with a victory over Monte, completing a season sweep of our cross county rivals. But that was not the only treat the team had in store for Coach Hinderlie. The girls spent their week planning to surprise their beloved coach with a heartfelt message of gratitude for all she has done for them. Following the game, each player read an attribute that Hinderlie embodies for each letter of her last name and presented her with a gift basket as a send off and thank you for her time as their coach before gathering one last time at center court to sing the fight song. Congratulations to the team on a great season, and thank you to Coach Hinderlie for the positive impact on our students!

On June 4, an Elma School District bus was involved in a traffic incident at a railroad crossing on 11th Street in Elma. The District asked the Elma Police Department to investigate the circumstances around this incident. The police investigation is now complete and they did not find fault with the driver‚Äôs actions. In an effort to ensure the highest level of student safety, the District is enhancing training guidelines to address how drivers should handle obstructed views at railroad crossings. We will be re-training this driver with these enhanced standards.

Contact:
Kevin Acuff
Superintendent
kacuff@eagles.edu
360-482-2822

On June 4, an Elma School District bus was involved in a traffic incident at a railroad crossing on 11th street in Elma. The District has asked the Elma Police Department to investigate the incident. The bus driver has been removed from driving responsibilities until the investigation is complete, at which time the transportation supervisor will take any appropriate personnel action. Our priority is student safety and our approach to this incident will be consistent with that priority. We will take every necessary step to prevent this from happening in the future. We will share the results of the investigation once it is complete.

post_text:
In other weekend Eagle News...

Junior Jill Bieker had an outstanding track meet performance Friday night and was named the Outstanding Female Athlete of the meet across more than 14 high schools competing! Jill set a stadium record, meet record, school record and ranked no. 1 in the state with a scorching time of 15.21 in 100 hurdles! Come cheer on Jill and our other track athletes, Thursday, May 9 at the Evergreen League Championship at Montesano High School! The SWW1A district track meet will be at Woodland High School, May 16.

And from our power lifting team, CONGRATS Baylee Crisp for setting the STATE RECORD as the 2019 State Squat Champion at 340 pounds. This is a huge accomplishment! Way to go Baylee! WOW!!!

Kevin Acuff
May 4, 2019 at 4:36 PM ¬∑

Lori Gumeson, Toby Spears, Stacey Schneidmiller and Morgan Thompson were honored last night at the Elma Chamber dinner. Lori, Toby and Stacey are three great educators for Elma School District and were recognized for their dedication and support of students. Morgan was honored as the Youth Citizen of the year for her leadership and community service work, including as Chair of the ASB Food Bowl Committee. It's a great day to be an Eagle!

Watch the Elma Girls Regional Basketball game vs Cashmere tonight live streamed on ELI SPORTS NETWORK - see information below. We have spoken with the network and here are the details to know in order to watch live. Cost is $10 for a monthly pass to their live games, this is a subscription, but you can cancel any time. Without a paid pass you can watch the game for free after 72 hours from game time. Tonight's game is on their schedule and will be streamed live for sure, only exceptions would be weather outages or Internet speeds (they have broadcast football from Wenatchee before so they think they should be good, although gyms sometimes cause issues with the streaming). You can also follow them on Twitter at #youresn

Good morning - This is to let you know we are aware of and are monitoring the weather situation. The National Weather Service is predicting snow to begin in Elma around noon and there may be several inches of snow prior to school being dismissed. At this time, it is our intention to transport students home at our regular dismissal times. Please be aware that if a decision was made to close school early, it would only be done with student safety as our paramount concern.

As always, we would announce any closures via our auto-dialer, which sends out emails, text messages and voice calls, via the FlashAlert system, with a link here, via local media and social media outlets.

Thank you for sharing your students with us and be safe.

http://www.flashalert.net/news.html?id=666

post_text:
Congratulations to VFW Essay Winners!!!
Jocelyn Rojas Zuniga, a 4th grade student in Mrs. Wells‚Äô class, won the District 5 VFW Essay Contest. She, and another classmate, Angelina Sanchez, entered the contest and won first, and second places respectively, at the local level. Each girl received a backpack filled with snacks, a journal, and a cash prize ($15 for 2nd & $25 for 1st).

Jocelyn's essay was also entered in the District level contest and won first prize there also! Her division was for 3rd-5th grades.

The VFW honored the Jocelyn and the other contest winners and their families at a luncheon in Olympia on Sunday, January 27th. Essays were read, medals were awarded and cash prizes were given. Jocelyn received a gold medal and $100 cash (her face in the picture below says it all!). Congrats to Jocelyn and Angelina! Thank you for representing our school and sharing your appreciation for our country!

post_text:
Food Bowl 2018 is in the books and we are super proud of our results!!! 11,120 pounds of food was collected and $17,086.82 was raised!

Thank you to all who donated time, money, and food. We truly appreciate you supporting our community and the hungry. Food banks in Malone, McCleary, and Elma received quality food and toiletries because of your generosity! We appreciate the efforts of all our Elma and McCleary students and staff. Thank you to Elma Transportation for donating and helping unload a bus of food loaded by our elementary students. Thank you to East County Rentals, Inc. for donating a Uhaul to get food from the schools to the food bank in Elma. Thank you to Gordon's for your donation of grocery bags for collecting food.

post_text: Friday, November 9th, the Elma Board of Directors met in an open, public meeting to interview and consider candidates for the open position created by the resignation of long serving board member, Rick Gravatt. The Board is pleased to announce the selection of Justin Cristelli to that position. All three candidates would have been excellent board members and we wish to thank and commend them for their interest in serving our district and community. Welcome Justin!
